    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Unfortunately I fear this would be quite complicated to achieve. There are two levels of cache:\r\n\r\n- search client: this is to prevent the request of already-requested queries\r\n- infinite hits: this is for display of pages that weren't in the current network request mostly\r\n\r\nthe infinite hits cache isn't in control of whether a network request happens, as that happens on every interaction with the search.\r\n\r\n\r\nA completely different design could solve this where the search client cache instead was saved in session storage, and infinite hits would call as many network requests (or cache as needed), but that's not possible easily right now. \r\n\r\nWhat I can see as a solution for you now is to pass the responsesCache: sessionStorageCache (that you can write based on https://github.com/algolia/algoliasearch-client-javascript/tree/master/packages/cache-browser-local-storage) in combination with your existing infinite hits cache. The information will then be cached twice, but it will avoid the initial network request.\r\n\r\n\r\nHope that helps, before we take the time to redesign this feature",
